◆ ImageQuality

enum tetraphilia::imaging_model::ImageQuality 
Controls the quality levels for bitmap image sampling in ARE

The quality level defines how the system combines rows or columns of a bitmap 
with existing pixels in a image when an application calls the Graphic.Paint method. 

The kIQExtremelyLow mode is typically used to preserve color in color bitmaps.  In most
implementations, it corresponds to a "nearest neighbor" implementation of image sampling.
Other interpolation modes do not make any guarantee to preserve color in color bitmaps and 
almost always create colors in the resultant image that will not exist in the original
image.  Also, kIQExtremelyLow can operate on any image natively regardless of its
CAIMPixelDescription (when in chunky mode).  

The other interpolation methods tetraphilia provides are progressively more sophisticated.
They require more processing of the source image than the proceeding modes in the list. They
tend to be slower than the previous ones, but they produce higher quality images.

ARE indicates a user interface that presents a tradeoff between quality and speed. The higher
the quality, the slower the algorithm runs.  This is not really unusual since Photoshop
does something similar for its JPEG UI.  The Photoshop UI presents the tradeoff between
file size and quality, while in ARE the tradeoff is between speed and quality.  There tetraphilia
cases when "average sampling/nearest neighbor sampling" is appropriate, and that
corresponds to the kIQExtremelyLow quality. This is the only guarantee ARE can make. 

Here is how these modes map into methods used by AGM and Acrobat: 


ARE                     AGM                                             Acrobat

kIQExtremelyLow,    "average sampling/nearest neighbor sampling"    uses AGM
kIQMedium,          uses ARE                                        bi-cubic (uses some internal code)
kIQMedium           "subsampling"*                                  uses AGM

* Notes on Subsampling:

1) Scale-only matrix:

AGM's subsampling occurs when the scale factor is greater than 1 but less than or equal to 2. This case produces almost identical results as running ARE with kIQMedium. For smaller scale factors, ARE with kIQMedium always produces a better result. When scaling an image up, AGM subsampling always produces inferior results compared to running ARE with kIQMedium.

2) Arbitrary affine matrix:

AGM's subsampling always produces inferior result compare to running ARE with kIQMedium.

The AGM subsampling algorithm was originally invented to address the problem of anti-aliased edges. It is appropriate when one wants sub-pixel coverage of the edge-pixels of an image. With the exception of this use of subsampling, there is nothing in the AGM that cannot be simulated in ARE. Even the intended effect of AGM's subsampling can be duplicated for the most part using ARE with kIQMedium.

See also
ImageSharpness

◆ ImageSharpness

enum tetraphilia::imaging_model::ImageSharpness

Controls the sharpening levels for bitmap image sampling in ARE

ImageSharpness increases/decreases the image sharpness. The kSSharpenMore applies a stronger sharpening effect than does the kSSharpen, while the kSSmoothMore applies a stronger smoothing effect than does the kSSmoothSlightly.

The sharpening does not preserving the overall smoothness of the image and could result in an excessive ring/halo effect in areas with sharp transitions in color or smoothness. The sharpening could result in blocky images specially when scaling an image up by a large factor. In such a case, it is better to leave the sharpening level at kSDefault. When sharpening is set to kSDefault, the system will select the appropriate sharpening effect based on various criterion.

◆ BlitToSurface()

template<typename surface_traits , typename signal_traits , typename op_type >
void tetraphilia::imaging_model::BlitToSurface ( const typename signal_traits::app_traits::int_geometry_traits::point_type &  clipOrigin,
const Constraints &  constraints,
const typename signal_traits::app_traits::int_geometry_traits::point_type &  sourceOrigin,
RasterPainter< signal_traits > &  source,
const typename signal_traits::app_traits::int_geometry_traits::point_type &  surfaceSize,
void *  baseAddress,
size_t  scanLineStride,
op_type   
)

Template function for rendering an instance of a model of the Raster Painter concept's color channel into an encoded surface. BlitToSurface() will typically be used by an implementation of a Surface's Blit() method.

BlitToSurface requires two template parameters: a surface_traits type, which must model the Surface Traits concept, and a source_type type, which must model the RasterPainter concept. Please see the documentation on the "Surface Traits" concept for details on how to create a correct model of the Surface Traits concept.

BlitToSurface takes nine parameters to describe the rendering:

clipOrigin: the point in surface space corresponding to the origin of the constraints and the clip. constraints: the constraints. The rendering will be clipped to the constraints' interest bounds. sourceOrigin: The point in surface space corresponding to the origin of the source. source: the RasterPainter being rendered to the surface. surfaceSize: the size of the surface. baseAddress: the base address of the surface. This is the location in memory of the pixel identified by the top left corner of surfaceBounds. scanLineStride: the distance in bytes between (x,y) and (x,y+1) in the surface.

◆ ScrollSurface()

template<typename surface_traits >
void tetraphilia::imaging_model::ScrollSurface ( const typename surface_traits::app_traits::int_geometry_traits::point_type &  delta,
const typename surface_traits::app_traits::int_geometry_traits::point_type &  surfaceSize,
void *  baseAddress,
size_t  scanLineStride 
)

Template function for scrolling the contents of a surface in any direction.

CONCEPT_Surface requires its models to provide a method called "ScrollBy" which is required to copy all the pixels in the surface to a new location in the same surface specified by an offset parameter. Only the pixels that are in the intersection of the surface's bounds and the surface's bounds translated by the delta should be modified.

This is a nontrivial operation, as the direction of the delta dictates the order in which memory can be copied. For example, if the y component is positive, the pixels must be copied in descending y order.

Some platforms provide support for this; others do not. Platforms that do not have this feature can use ScrollSurface, which works for any direction.

Template Parameters
surface_traitsA model of CONCEPT_surface_traits which describes the geometry of the pixels in this surface.
Parameters
deltaA point describing the direction of the scroll. Negative values are up and to the left; positive values are down and to the right.
surfaceSizeThe size of the surface, in pixels.
baseAddressA pointer to the top left pixel in the surface.
scanLineStrideThe distance in bytes between the pixel at (x,y) and the pixel at (x,y+1).

inline

Test whether or not two pixel buffer layouts have compatible signal counts.

Returns true if a destination pixel buffer with the given layout can, without loss of information, have data copied from a source with the given layout into it. Note that this is not a symmetric relation! A replicated buffer can be used as a source for a non-replicated buffer, but not vice versa.

Helper function for PixelBufferLayout overload of SignalCountCompatible.
